      <hedline>
        <hl1>Pension Shortfall In New Jersey</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>David Langer letter responds to April 4 article noting that New Jersey has been diverting billions of dollars from its pension fund for state and local workers into other government purposes over last 15 years; suggests expanding Social Security by raising its benefit formula to 70 percent of final average pay and raising taxable wage base to $150,000 and incorporating all plans--public and private</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''New Jersey Diverts Billions, Endangering Pension Fund'' (front page, April 4) notes that ''New Jersey has been diverting billions of dollars from its pension fund for state and local workers into other government purposes over the last 15 years, using a variety of unorthodox transactions authorized by the Legislature and by governors from both political parties.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''New Jersey Diverts Billions, Endangering Pension Fund'' (front page, April 4) notes that ''New Jersey has been diverting billions of dollars from its pension fund for state and local workers into other government purposes over the last 15 years, using a variety of unorthodox transactions authorized by the Legislature and by governors from both political parties.''</p>
        <p>One simple long-term solution to the general problem is to expand Social Security by raising its benefit formula to 70 percent of final average pay and raising the taxable wage base to $150,000 and incorporating all plans -- public and private.</p>
        <p>Given the sound way that Social Security operates, there is little opportunity for fraudulent practices, and workers are freed of worry about their retirement income. Assets in current plans can be used as an offset to keep costs down during the transition period.</p>
        <p>David Langer  New York, April 4, 2007</p>
        <p>The writer is a consulting actuary.</p>
      </block>
